{{for|the politician|Chiang Hsiao-yen}} {{Chinese name|[[Zhang (surname)|Chang]]}} {{Infobox Chinese-language singer and actor | name = Chang Hsiao-yen | image = Hsiao-Yen Chang.JPG | caption = | gender = female | background = show_host_or_hostess | tradchinesename = 張小燕 | simpchinesename = 张小燕 | pinyinchinesename = Zhāng Xiǎoyàn | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1948|8|11|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Shanghai]], [[Republic of China (1912–49)|China]] | nationality = Taiwanese | othername = Zhang Xiaoyan | alma_mater = Blessed Imelda's School | occupation = {{hlist|[[Television presenter|Host]]|[[actress]]|[[businesswoman]]|[[radio DJ]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.epochtimes.com/b5/7/10/16/n1869420.htm | title=飛碟11週年台慶星光熠熠 張小燕重返錄音室 | work=Epoch Times | date=16 October 2007 | accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref>}} | yearsactive = 1953&ndash;present | spouse = {{unbulleted list|{{marriage|Pei Chen-kun |1980|1986|reason=divorced}}|{{marriage|Peng Kuo-Hua|1990|2001|reason=died}}}} | partner = | children = 1 | parents = | website = | awards = }}
'''Chang Hsiao-yen''' ({{zh|t=張小燕|s=张小燕|p=Zhāng Xiǎoyàn)}}; born 11 August 1948) is a [[Taiwan]]ese television host and actress. Born in Shanghai, China, Chang relocated to Taiwan after the [[Chinese Civil War]] where she started her acting career at the age of five as a child actress in cinema. In 1958, she received her first Best Child Actress award at the [[Asia Pacific Film Festival]], a recognition she earned for three consecutive years and which placed her alongside notable child stars such as [[Josephine Siao]], [[Lydia Shum]], [[Fung Bo Bo]] and [[Connie Chan]]. Since the 1980s, Chang has become a household name in Taiwan after hosting the [[Chinese Television System|CTS]] variety show ''Variety 100'' (綜藝100) which is one of the most successful shows in the television history of Taiwan. She is also known for her work as the host of highly rated variety shows such as ''Weekend Pie'' (週末派), ''Super Sunday'' (超級星期天), ''Million-Dollar Class'' (百萬小學堂) and ''SS Hsiao-yen Night'' (SS小燕之夜).<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.cts.com.tw/cts/english/201106/201106060751033.html | title=THE ULTIMATE ENTERTAINER | work=CTS | date=6 June 2011 | accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref>
In addition to her television and film work, Chang co-founded the record label Forward Music (豐華唱片) which launched the singing career of then newcomers [[A-mei]] and [[Tao Ching-Ying]]. She is also a mentor of television hosts [[Mickey Huang]], [[Pu Hsueh-liang]] and [[Bowie Tsang]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chinatimes.com/newspapers/20150909000710-260112 | title=阿亮迎半百 壯膽啵小燕謝恩 | work=China Times | date=9 September 2015 | accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref>
In an annual poll conducted by [[Reader's Digest]] in 2015, Chang was voted the most trusted Taiwanese variety show host.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chinatimes.com/newspapers/20150626000805-260112 | title=謝震武張小燕 雙掛最受信任主持人 | work=China Times | date=26 June 2015 | accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref>
She was formerly the managing director of television channels [[TVBS Entertainment Channel]] and [[Azio TV]], and the President of radio network UFO Network Broadcasting (飛碟廣播). She currently serves as the President of artiste management company Grand Pan Communication Co. (大鵬傳播事業有限公司) and Forward Music.
