{{Infobox person | name = Jean-Michel Goudard |image = |birth_name =F | birth_date = {{birth date|1939|11|13|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Montpellier]], [[France]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality =French | other_names = | known_for = | education = | employer = | occupation ={{hlist|PR consultant|}} | title = | salary = | networth = | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | children = | parents = | relatives = | box_width = }}
'''Jean-Michel Goudard''' is a French [[Public relations]] [[consultant]], who is the current [[Presudent]] and [[Chairman]] of the board of [[BBDO]] Paris.
Goudard was born in [[Montpellier]], [[France]] on 13 November 1939. He graduated from [[HEC Business School]] in 1962, became a Navy Officer in 1964, and brand manager at [[Procter and Gamble]] in 1965, managing director of [[Young and Rubicam]]<ref name="CoignardGuichard2000">{{cite book|last1=Coignard|first1=Sophie|last2=Guichard|first2=Marie-Thérèse|title=French connections: networks of influence|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GVyohk7knogC&pg=PA110|accessdate=16 April 2011|year=2000|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=978-1-892941-02-2|page=110}}</ref> in France in 1970, he created with Bernard Roux, Jacques Seguela and Alain Cayzac the advertising agency [[RSCG]] (Roux Seguele Cayzac Goudard) which grew into an international network agency. Goudard is also a hobbyist bullfighter. <ref name=Campaignlive>{{cite web|last=Hall|first=Emma|title=CLOSE-UP: NEWSMAKER/JEAN-MICHEL GOUDARD; Bon viveur poised to prove his worth in America|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/close-up-newsmaker-jean-michel-goudard-bon-viveur-poised-prove-worth-america/20822|work=Campaignlive|accessdate=July 21, 2018|date=1995-12-08}}</ref>
Together with Bernard Brochand, he made the winning campaign of [[Jacques Chirac]] and his gaullist party RPR "Oui à la France qui gagne" in 1978. He did it again in 1986 with the campaign "Vivement Demain". The same year, he published his book "Je vous salue fiascos" (Jean-Claude Lattes) about his own fiascos in advertising. In 1988, Jacques Chirac, then Prime Minister, asked him to manage his presidential campaign against [[François Mitterrand]]. In 1991, he became the president of Euro-RSCG International, covering the whole worldwide network outside France. In 1995, he managed again the presidential campaign of Jacques Chirac ("La France pour tous"), and, immediately after the election of Jacques Chirac as President of France, he left Euro-RSCG and France to live in [[New York City]], for 10 years, as president of BBDO International. He retired in April 2006 to run the presidential campaign of [[Nicolas Sarkozy]], and became so close with the President that he even attended the G7 summit. <ref>{{cite web|title=Jean-Michel Goudard, the strategist.|url=https://www.lesechos.fr/15/04/2009/LesEchos/20405-050-ECH_jean-michel-goudard--le-stratege-.htm|accessdate=July 21, 2018|date=2009-04-15}}</ref>. Goudard created the claim "Ensemble, tout devient possible" ("Together, everything becomes possible")<ref name=Europe1>{{cite web|title=Sarkoleaks: who is Jean-Michel Goudard?|url=http://www.europe1.fr/politique/sarkoleaks-qui-est-jean-michel-goudard-1905349|accessdate=July 21, 2018|date=2014-04-05}}</ref>. Immediately after Sarkozy's election, in 2007, he retired in [[Switzerland]] in [[Rolle]] (canton of [[Vaud]]). In 2008, President Sarkozy asked him to become his Chief Strategy Officer. Goudard accepted. He came back to France to work at the [[Elysée Palace]]. In 2016 Jean-Michel Goudard was indicted in the affair of the polls of the Elysée for his work with Nicolas Sarkozy. <ref name=Lemonde>{{cite web|title=Jean-Michel Goudard in turn indicted in the polls case of the Elysee|url=https://www.lemonde.fr/politique/article/2016/02/03/jean-michel-goudard-a-son-tour-mis-en-examen-dans-l-affaire-des-sondages-de-l-elysee_4858876_823448.html|accessdate=July 21, 2018|date=2016-05-02}}</ref>
