Dr. '''Mohamed Zahir Hussain''',([[Dhivehi language|Dhivehi]]:ޑރ. މުޙައްމަދު ޒާހިރު ޙުސައިން) is the [[Chancellor]] of [[Maldives National University]]<ref>http://sun.mv/english/1987</ref> and the former Minister of Education<ref>{{cite news |title=A Minister Who Goes To School Thrice A Week |work=[[New Straits Times]] |date=2 June 1989 |page=2 }}</ref> as well as the Minister of Youth and Sports<ref>{{cite news |title=Lankan sportsmen invited to Maldives |url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2002/09/20/new26.html |work=Daily News (Sri Lanka) |date=20 September 2002 |accessdate=16 March 2011 }}</ref> of the [[Maldives]]. He resigned from the post of Youth Minister in the year 2004 but was again appointed as a senior minister (a special advisor to the president)<ref>{{cite news |title=The President appoints three Senior Ministers and four Ministers |url=http://www.maldivesinfo.gov.mv/home/files/bulletinx_det.php?id_news=983 |work=Maldives News Bulletin |publisher=Department of Information |date=20 April 2008 |accessdate=16 March 2011 }}</ref> in 2006 and served in the cabinet of [[President of the Maldives|President]] [[Maumoon Abdul Gayoom]] until 2008 presidential election. In 2008, he was conferred the distinguished "Order of Izzuddin" by [[President of the Maldives|President]] [[Maumoon Abdul Gayoom]].<ref>http://www.maldivesinfo.gov.mv/home/files/bulletinx_det.php?id_news=1070</ref> He is also the Chairman/Owner of the newspaper [[Haveeru Daily]] which was established in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haveeru.com.mv/haveeru/ |title=About Haveeru Daily |publisher=[[Haveeru Daily]] |accessdate=16 March 2011 }}</ref>

